thread.title: Brisbane records the highest auction clearance rate it has achieved in six years
thread.title_full: Brisbane records the highest auction clearance rate it has achieved in six years

author: Michelle Hele Network Online Real Estate Editor
title: Brisbane records the highest auction clearance rate it has achieved in six years
text:
AUCTIONS are still proving popular with buyers as Brisbane chalked up its highest clearance rate in six years.
While Sydney and Melbourne are traditionally the strongest auction markets in Australia, Brisbane returned a preliminary auction clearance of 66 per cent - its highest since 2009.
There were 159 properties scheduled to be auction in Brisbane last week with resulted recorded for 47 of those.
Sales included an Ipswich home which was built in the late 19th century. The home at 100 Mt Crosby Rd, Tivoli sold for $650,000.
A home at 105 Villiers St, New Farm sold for $2.4 million.
The four-bedroom home has three bathrooms and is on a 405sq m block.
Nationally the auction clearance rate for the combined capital cities was 77.7 per cent with 1998 auctions held during the past week.
A developer was very keen to secure this home at Granville paying $1.53 million above reserve to buy it. Source: Supplied
Sydney’s clearance rate kept pushing past the 80 per cent figure, chalking 82.7 per cent last week, including a home at 33 William S, Granville which sold for $1.53 million above its reserve price.
A developer paid $2.781 million for the property, with the intention of knocking it down.
The home was on a 1440sq m side. More than 100 people gathered to watch the auction of the property which has dual access and is next door to Granville RSL Club.
This home at 34 Lindsay Ave, Murrumbeena sold under the hammer for $1.485 million. Source: Supplied
Melbourne returned a strong 76.5 per cent clearance rate which included the sale of a five-bedroom home at 34 Lindsay Ave, Murrumbeena for $1.485 million.
It was declared on the market at $1.37 million.
The home, known as Romany still retains some of its period features but has been extended and renovated.
Perth’s clearance rate of 80 per cent appears strong, but that was only based on the results of 10 auctions.
Adelaide continued to achieve strong auction clearance rates with 60.6 per cent of properties selling under the hammer last week.
